<section>
    <h2>Description</h2>
    <p>The <code>&lt;source&gt;</code> element is an empty element that specifies media resources for <code>&lt;picture&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;video&gt;</code>, and <code>&lt;audio&gt;</code> elements. It allows browsers to choose the most appropriate media file based on format support, media queries, or other criteria.</p>

    <p>The browser evaluates <code>&lt;source&gt;</code> elements in order and uses the first one that matches. This enables progressive enhancement with modern formats while maintaining compatibility with older browsers.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>When to Use</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Format fallback</strong> - Serve modern formats (WebP, AVIF, VP9) with older format fallbacks</li>
      <li><strong>Art direction</strong> - Different images for different viewport sizes (with picture)</li>
      <li><strong>Resolution switching</strong> - Different resolutions for different pixel densities</li>
      <li><strong>Codec support</strong> - Alternative video/audio codecs for browser compatibility</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

